You need to block HTTP traffic from IP 203.0.113.50 while keeping HTTPS allowed. What should you do?', '["Create a rule with priority 50 to deny HTTP from 203.0.113.50","Create a rule with priority 150 to deny HTTP from 203.0.113.50","Modify the existing HTTP rule to exclude 203.0.113.50","Create a rule with priority 1100 to deny HTTP from 203.0.113.50"]', '[0]', 'NSG rules are processed in priority order (lower numbers first). To block specific traffic before the general allow rule, create a deny rule with priority 50, which will be processed before the priority 100 allow rule.', '{"correct":"NSG rules are evaluated in ascending priority order (100, 200, 300, etc.). To block specific traffic that would otherwise be allowed by a general rule, you must place the deny rule with a lower priority number so it''s evaluated first. Priority 50 will be processed before priority 100, effectively blocking HTTP from the specific IP.","why_others_wrong":{"1":"Priority 150 would be evaluated after priority 100 (Allow HTTP), so the traffic would already be allowed and never reach the deny rule.","2":"NSG rules cannot exclude specific IPs within a single rule - you need separate rules for different source IP ranges.","3":"Priority 1100 would be evaluated after all other rules, including the Allow HTTP rule at priority 100, making it ineffective."}}', '{"title":"Network security groups - Azure Virtual Network","url":"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-network/network-security-groups-overview"}', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', TRUE) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
