A packet matches rules in all three collections. Which rule is applied?', '["The rule with the lowest priority number within each collection","Only the NAT rule (processed first)","All matching rules are applied in sequence","The most specific rule regardless of collection type"]', '[1]', 'Azure Firewall processes rule collections in order: NAT rules first, then Network rules, then Application rules. Processing stops when the first match is found. Since NAT rules are processed first, only the NAT rule would be applied.', '{"correct":"Azure Firewall uses a deterministic rule processing order: DNAT rules are processed first, followed by Network rules, then Application rules. This order ensures that destination NAT translation occurs before any filtering decisions. Once a rule matches and an action is taken (allow, deny, or DNAT), processing stops and subsequent rule collections are not evaluated for that packet.","why_others_wrong":{"0":"While priority numbers matter within a collection, the collection type order takes precedence. NAT rules are always processed before network or application rules regardless of priority numbers.","2":"Azure Firewall follows a ''first match wins'' principle. Once a rule matches and an action is determined, no further rules are processed for that packet.","3":"Rule specificity doesn''t override the collection processing order. NAT rules are always processed first regardless of how specific network or application rules might be."}}', '{"title":"Azure Firewall rule processing logic","url":"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/firewall/rule-processing"}', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', TRUE) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
