What is the most efficient subnet allocation?', '["A: /22, B: /23, C: /24, D: /26","A: /21, B: /22, C: /24, D: /26","A: /22, B: /23, C: /24, D: /28","A: /20, B: /22, C: /23, D: /26"]', '[0]', 'Subnet A needs /22 (1022 hosts), B needs /23 (510 hosts), C needs /24 (254 hosts), D needs /26 (62 hosts). This allocation is efficient and meets all requirements with minimal waste.', '{"correct":"/22 provides 1022 usable hosts (sufficient for 1000), /23 provides 510 usable hosts (sufficient for 500), /24 provides 254 usable hosts (sufficient for 200), and /26 provides 62 usable hosts (sufficient for 50). This allocation minimizes IP address waste while meeting all requirements.","why_others_wrong":{"1":"/21 for Subnet A provides 2046 hosts, which is excessive for 1000 hosts requirement and wastes address space.","2":"/28 for Subnet D provides only 14 hosts, which is insufficient for the 50 hosts requirement.","3":"/20 for Subnet A provides 4094 hosts, which is excessive and wastes significant address space."}}', '{"title":"Virtual network planning - Azure Virtual Network","url":"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-network/virtual-network-vnet-plan-design-arm"}', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', TRUE) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
