A packet matches a DNAT rule, a network rule, and an application rule. Which rule is processed and applied?', '["The rule with the lowest priority number (DNAT rule)","All matching rules are applied in sequence","Only the DNAT rule is processed, others are ignored","The most specific rule is applied regardless of priority"]', '[2]', 'Azure Firewall processes rule types in a specific order: DNAT, then Network, then Application. Once a DNAT rule matches, it''s applied and processing stops.', '{"correct":"Azure Firewall uses a hierarchical rule processing order: DNAT rules are processed first, then Network rules, then Application rules. When a packet matches a DNAT rule, the destination NAT is applied and the packet is allowed through the firewall. No further rule processing occurs for that packet, even if it would match network or application rules.","why_others_wrong":{"0":"While DNAT rules do have the lowest priority number, the processing is based on rule type hierarchy, not priority numbers within collections.","1":"Azure Firewall uses deterministic rule processing - only one rule type is applied per packet, not sequential application.","3":"Rule specificity is not the determining factor - the rule type hierarchy (DNAT > Network > Application) determines processing order."}}', '{"title":"Azure Firewall rule processing","url":"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/firewall/rule-processing"}', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', '2025-08-17T02:46:25.562325+00:00', TRUE) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;


